Algorithm considerations

Features seem to be highly correlated, raising multicollinearity. As we do not want to suppress any of these characteristics for the purposes of interpretability and impact on emissions, we will use the following algorithms, which are well suited to multicollinearity situations:

  • Random Forest
  • Ridge Regression
  • Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) Regressor

As the targets appear to be highly correlated, and since we do not want to remove any of these target values for interpretation purposes and an overall view of all these pollutants' emissions implications, it suggests that the Multi-Output Regression technique may be better.

The models have been selected for comparison purposes to provide decision-makers with the model or models that could assist in identifying the factors influencing emissions and offer insights into their future evolution. This will facilitate the necessary actions to reduce pollution caused by roads.

For evaluations, we will use some metrics outlined below.

Evaulations metrics considerations

As we are going to use Regression Supervised Machines Learning, we are going to use the following metrics to evaluate the algorithms performace:

Mean Absolute Error (MAE) is the average absolute difference between actual and predicted values :

$$\frac 1n\sum_{i=1}^n|y_i-\hat{y}_i|$$

R Squared (R²) is the coefficient of determination. It represents the proportion of the variance in y that is predictable from the independent variables (X).

$$1 - \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n (y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2}{\sum_{i=1}^n (y_i - \bar{y})^2}$$

Mean Squared Error (MSE) is the mean square error. It penalises larger errors more heavily than MAE since it squares the errors.

$$\frac 1n\sum_{i=1}^n(y_i-\hat{y}_i)^2$$

Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) is the square root of the mean error squared. It is the square root of MSE and gives an error measure in the same units as the data.

$$\sqrt{\frac 1n\sum_{i=1}^n(y_i-\hat{y}_i)^2}$$
  • MAE is the average error.
  • R² quantifies how well the regression model fits the observed data
  • MSE penalise larger errors, which tends to be useful in the real world.
  • RMSE can be interpreted in the same units as ‘y’.

R^2 value that tend 1 means the model explains all the variability in the dependent variable. For the other metrics, lower values indicate better performance and mean better predictions.

Feature Importance Insights

The Ridge regressor shows that petrol and diesel vehicles, especially cars, PHVs, and buses, mainly contribute to CO₂, PM10, PM2.5, and NO₂ emissions.

Diesel cars dominate NO₂ emissions, while petrol PHVs and cars are key drivers for Particulate Matter.

Electric vehicles consistently show negative coefficients, indicating a reduction in all pollutants. Urban area features have smaller but varied impacts.

Overall Interpretation

✅ Performance:

Ridge performs well, with good R² values and low error metrics across all pollutants.
The model captures most of the variance in air pollutant levels, making it a strong predictive tool.

⚠️ Potential Areas for Improvement:

Hyperparameter tuning could further refine predictions.
Compared to other algorithms (Random Forests, MLP), Ridge is less challenging to interpret. Feature importance insights show the contributions of many characteristics in emissions.

Step 2.2.3: Multi-layer Perceptron Multi-Output Regressor¶

In [61]:
# Scale training data and store the scaler
X_train_scaled, y_train_scaled, scaler_X, scaler_y = utils.scale_data(X_train, y_train, fit_scaler=True)

mlp_pipeline = Pipeline([
        ('scaler', scaler_X),
        ('mlp', MLPRegressor(max_iter=500, random_state=42))
    ])

# Wrap the pipeline with TransformedTargetRegressor to scale the target values.
# This ensures that during prediction, the outputs are automatically inverse transformed
# back to the original (unnormalized) space.
mlp_model = TransformedTargetRegressor(regressor=mlp_pipeline, transformer=scaler_y)

mlp_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

Step 2.3: Models tuning¶

In this part, we will attempt to enhance all the models by applying hyperparameter techniques to find the best settings to develop robust models.

We will perform hyperparameter tuning using GridSearchCV and K-Fold techniques to determine the optimal settings and avoid scenarios of underfitting or overfitting.

Interpretation on tuning

Except for some metrics, like the metrics of Random Forest, the tuning techniques have slightly enhanced the performance of the various models, as evidenced by the comparisons between the previous and new metrics. These changes in performance, even for slightly increased metrics, probably indicate that our tuned models are unlikely to be overfit models.

The Ridge Regressor's performance was virtually unchanged after hyperparameter tuning. R² and MSE saw only negligible improvements - co2_avg MAE and RMSE improved by just 0.000047 and 0.000070 - while pm10_avg and pm25_avg remained almost the same, indicating the initial model was already highly optimised.

Hyperparameter tuning only marginally affected the Random Forest model's performance, with nearly unchanged MAE, R², MSE and RMSE across pollutants. Minor increases in error metrics for pm10_avg and pm25_avg, along with a slight drop in R², suggest that the initial model was already well-optimised.

Hyperparameter tuning yielded a slight improvement in overall model performance. R² scores increased for all pollutants while MAE, MSE and RMSE decreased for pm10_avg, pm25_avg and no2_avg, indicating enhanced prediction accuracy. A minor MAE rise for co2_avg was outweighed by gains in other areas, confirming a consistent improvement, particularly for acceptable particulate predictions.

One could choose to combine these models for different pollutants to achieve optimal predictions while handling interpretations. For example, a combination of the MLP regressor and Ridge regressor can be used to link the interpretative strength of Ridge models with the performance strength of the MLP and provide stakeholders with models that combine good predictions and interpretability.

Feature Importance Overview

CO₂ Emissions

Across all models, diesel and petrol vehicles emerged as major contributors. The Ridge model emphasised hybrid vehicles (PHVs) and diesel cars with strong positive coefficients. The MLP model highlighted the impact of buses and HGVs (rigid and articulated). Random Forest revealed high importance for diesel LGVs and electric cars.

PM10 and PM2.5 Emissions

Petrol and diesel vehicles, motorcycles, and buses consistently showed influence across Ridge and MLP models. The Ridge model showed negative coefficients for some electric vehicles, while the MLP model identified motorcycles and HGVs as key contributors. Interestingly, Random Forest ranked electric cars highly for both PM10 and PM2.5, potentially indicating proxy effects like traffic presence or non-exhaust particulate sources.

NO₂ Emissions

Diesel cars dominate Ridge and Random Forest models, with high positive coefficients and importance scores. PHVs and LGVs also played notable roles. The MLP model highlighted petrol cars, diesel PHVs, and rigid HGVs as major contributors.

Overall outcomes and future perspectives

In conclusion, this study successfully demonstrates the power of machine learning for predicting atmospheric emissions using the 2019 LAEI. We achieved robust predictive performance across multiple pollutants by integrating thorough data cleaning, practical implementation, and rigorous model tuning. Our analysis revealed that petrol, diesel, and heavy goods vehicles are key contributors to emissions, providing actionable insights for environmental policy. These results lay a strong foundation for extending the approach to longer historical periods and enhancing model interpretability, ultimately supporting more informed and sustainable urban planning decisions.

As the impact of electric vehicles remains comparatively low, this highlights the need to promote more Electric vehicles. Predictions for the coming years, based on this study, may help quantify the effects of these elements on pollution and implement gradual measures according to the impact of these various characteristics.

Future actions to consider involve incorporating explainable AI (XAI) or employing techniques such as SHAP or LIME to enhance interpretative clarity, thereby enabling decision-makers to act with greater confidence.
